Yes, you can use an `else` branch instead of handling all the remaining cases individually in the `when` expression. The `else` branch will catch all the cases that are not explicitly handled by the other branches.

Here's how you can modify the `handleLoginResponse` function using an `else` branch:

```kotlin
private fun handleLoginResponse(response: ApiResponse<OrderingLoginResponseStruct>?) {
    when (response) {
        is ApiResponse.Success -> {
            orderInfoLoading?.visibility = VISIBLE
            response.data?.sessionKey?.let { sessionKey ->
                sharedViewModel.setSessionKey(sessionKey)
                val sessionKeyRequest = OrderingRequest(sessionKey)
                loginView.getOrderInfo(sessionKeyRequest)
                loginView.orderInfoResponse.observe(viewLifecycleOwner) { orderInfoResponse ->
                    handleOrderInfoResponse(orderInfoResponse)
                }
            }
        }

        is ApiResponse.Error -> {
            val errorMessage = response.message ?: "An error occurred"
            showToast(errorMessage)
        }

        is ApiResponse.ErrorLogin -> {
            val errorMessage = response.data?.message ?: "Login error occurred"
            showToast(errorMessage)
        }

        else -> {
            // Handle all other cases (Loading, NoDataError, ErrorSendOrderDate, UnknownError, null)
            val errorMessage = "An unexpected error occurred"
            showToast(errorMessage)
        }
    }
}
```

In this version, we've replaced the individual branches for `is Loading`, `is NoDataError`, `is ErrorSendOrderDate`, `is UnknownError`, and `null` with a single `else` branch. The `else` branch will catch all the cases that are not explicitly handled by the `is ApiResponse.Success`, `is ApiResponse.Error`, or `is ApiResponse.ErrorLogin` branches.

Inside the `else` branch, you can handle all the remaining cases in a generic way. In the example above, we're displaying a Toast message with a generic error message ("An unexpected error occurred").

Using an `else` branch can be a more concise way to handle the remaining cases, especially if you don't need to handle them differently. However, if you need to perform specific actions for each case, it's better to handle them individually for better readability and maintainability.

To reset the flag and allow user interaction again after handling the API response, you can call the `clearFlags` method on the `Window` object of the current activity. This will remove the `FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE` flag that was set earlier to prevent user interaction during the API call.

Here's an example of how you can do it in the `handleLoginResponse` function:

```kotlin
private fun handleLoginResponse(response: ApiResponse<OrderingLoginResponseStruct>?) {
    when (response) {
        is ApiResponse.Success -> {
            orderInfoLoading?.visibility = VISIBLE
            response.data?.sessionKey?.let { sessionKey ->
                sharedViewModel.setSessionKey(sessionKey)
                val sessionKeyRequest = OrderingRequest(sessionKey)
                loginView.getOrderInfo(sessionKeyRequest)
                loginView.orderInfoResponse.observe(viewLifecycleOwner) { orderInfoResponse ->
                    handleOrderInfoResponse(orderInfoResponse)
                }
            }
        }

        is ApiResponse.Error -> {
            val errorMessage = response.message ?: "An error occurred"
            showToast(errorMessage)
            clearNotTouchableFlag()
        }

        is ApiResponse.ErrorLogin -> {
            val errorMessage = response.data?.message ?: "Login error occurred"
            showToast(errorMessage)
            clearNotTouchableFlag()
        }

        else -> {
            val errorMessage = "An unexpected error occurred"
            showToast(errorMessage)
            clearNotTouchableFlag()
        }
    }
}

private fun clearNotTouchableFlag() {
    requireActivity().window.clearFlags(WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE)
}
```

In this example, we've added a `clearNotTouchableFlag` function that calls `requireActivity().window.clearFlags(WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE)`. This line of code removes the `FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE` flag from the current activity's window, allowing user interaction again.

We've called the `clearNotTouchableFlag` function in the `is ApiResponse.Error`, `is ApiResponse.ErrorLogin`, and `else` branches of the `when` expression. This ensures that the flag is cleared and user interaction is enabled after handling the API response, regardless of the response type.

You can call the `clearNotTouchableFlag` function in other parts of your code as well, wherever you need to re-enable user interaction after completing a task or operation that required disabling user interaction temporarily.

You're getting two "Login failed" toasts after pressing the Login button twice because the `handleLoginResponse` function is being called twice, once for each button press.

When you press the Login button, the `loginView.getUserLogin(login)` function is called, which initiates the API call. The `loginView.userLoginResponse.observe(viewLifecycleOwner) { response -> handleLoginResponse(response) }` line sets up an observer for the `userLoginResponse` LiveData object. Whenever the `userLoginResponse` LiveData object is updated with a new value, the `handleLoginResponse` function is called with the new value.

If you press the Login button twice before the first API call completes, the `loginView.getUserLogin(login)` function will be called twice, initiating two separate API calls. When each API call completes and updates the `userLoginResponse` LiveData object, the `handleLoginResponse` function will be called twice, resulting in two "Login failed" toasts.

To prevent this behavior, you should reset the `userLoginResponse` LiveData object before initiating a new API call. This way, the observer will only be triggered once for the latest API call, and you won't get duplicate toasts.

Here's how you can modify the code to reset the `userLoginResponse` before initiating a new API call:

```kotlin
with(binding) {
    loginButton.setOnClickListener {
        viewLifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope.launch(Dispatchers.Main) {
            var isInternetAvailable = checkInternetAvailability()
            //isInternetAvailable = true
            if (isInternetAvailable) {
                // Internet is available, proceed with network operations
                if (checkUsernamePassword()) {
                    // Sets the required username and password to be sent within the Login Api call.
                    requireActivity().window.setFlags(
                        WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE,
                        WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE
                    )
                    it.hideKeyboard()
                    // Gets and sets the user entered username and password.
                    val usernameText = username.text.toString()
                    val passwordText = password.text.toString()
                    val login = LoginRequest(usernameText, passwordText)
                    // Initiates the Login Api call, passing the above username and password.
                    loginView.resetLoginState() // Reset the userLoginResponse LiveData
                    loginView.getUserLogin(login)
                    loginView.userLoginResponse.observe(viewLifecycleOwner) { response ->
                        handleLoginResponse(response)
                    }
                }
            } else {
                showNoInternetToast()
            }
        }
    }
}
```

In this modified code, we've added `loginView.resetLoginState()` before calling `loginView.getUserLogin(login)`. The `resetLoginState` function should reset the `userLoginResponse` LiveData object to its initial state (e.g., `null` or a default value).

By resetting the `userLoginResponse` LiveData object before initiating a new API call, you ensure that the observer is only triggered once for the latest API call, preventing duplicate toasts or other unintended behavior.

