Yes, it is possible to show a dialog from an overflow menu in Android. You can achieve this by setting up an `OnMenuItemClickListener` for the overflow menu item and then displaying the dialog when the menu item is clicked.

Here's an example of how you can implement this:

1. First, define the overflow menu item in your menu resource file (e.g., `menu_overflow.xml`):

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<menu xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android">
    <item
        android:id="@+id/menu_item_show_dialog"
        android:title="Show Dialog" />
</menu>
```

2. In your activity or fragment class, inflate the menu and set up the `OnMenuItemClickListener`:

```kotlin
class YourActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.your_layout)

        // Inflate the overflow menu
        val overflowMenu = PopupMenu(this, null)
        overflowMenu.menuInflater.inflate(R.menu.menu_overflow, overflowMenu.menu)

        // Set up the OnMenuItemClickListener
        overflowMenu.setOnMenuItemClickListener { menuItem ->
            when (menuItem.itemId) {
                R.id.menu_item_show_dialog -> {
                    showDialog()
                    true
                }
                else -> false
            }
        }

        // Show the overflow menu when needed (e.g., on a button click)
        val overflowButton = findViewById<Button>(R.id.overflowButton)
        overflowButton.setOnClickListener {
            overflowMenu.show()
        }
    }

    private fun showDialog() {
        // Create and show the dialog
        val dialog = AlertDialog.Builder(this)
            .setTitle("Dialog Title")
            .setMessage("This is a dialog shown from the overflow menu.")
            .setPositiveButton("OK") { _, _ -> }
            .create()
        dialog.show()
    }
}
```

In this example:

1. We inflate the overflow menu from the `menu_overflow.xml` resource file using `PopupMenu`.
2. We set up an `OnMenuItemClickListener` for the `PopupMenu` and handle the click event for the "Show Dialog" menu item by calling the `showDialog()` function.
3. We show the overflow menu when needed, for example, when a button is clicked.
4. The `showDialog()` function creates and displays an `AlertDialog` using the `AlertDialog.Builder`.

When the user clicks the "Show Dialog" menu item from the overflow menu, the `showDialog()` function will be called, and the dialog will be displayed.

You can customize the dialog's appearance, behavior, and content by modifying the `AlertDialog.Builder` code in the `showDialog()` function.

Note that this example uses an `AlertDialog`, but you can also create and show other types of dialogs, such as `DialogFragment` or custom dialogs, by modifying the `showDialog()` function accordingly.

The error `java.lang.IllegalStateException: MenuPopupHelper cannot be used without an anchor` occurs when you try to show a `PopupMenu` without providing an anchor view. The anchor view is the view that the `PopupMenu` will be anchored to and positioned relative to.

To resolve this issue, you need to provide an anchor view when creating the `PopupMenu` instance. Here's how you can modify your code:

```kotlin
class YourActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.your_layout)

        // Find the anchor view (e.g., a button or an overflow icon)
        val anchorView = findViewById<View>(R.id.anchorView)

        // Inflate the overflow menu
        val overflowMenu = PopupMenu(this, anchorView)
        overflowMenu.menuInflater.inflate(R.menu.menu_overflow, overflowMenu.menu)

        // Set up the OnMenuItemClickListener
        overflowMenu.setOnMenuItemClickListener { menuItem ->
            when (menuItem.itemId) {
                R.id.menu_item_show_dialog -> {
                    showDialog()
                    true
                }
                else -> false
            }
        }

        // Show the overflow menu when needed (e.g., on a button click)
        anchorView.setOnClickListener {
            overflowMenu.show()
        }
    }

    private fun showDialog() {
        // Create and show the dialog
        val dialog = AlertDialog.Builder(this)
            .setTitle("Dialog Title")
            .setMessage("This is a dialog shown from the overflow menu.")
            .setPositiveButton("OK") { _, _ -> }
            .create()
        dialog.show()
    }
}
```

In this modified code:

1. We find the anchor view (e.g., a button or an overflow icon) using `findViewById`.
2. We create the `PopupMenu` instance and pass the anchor view as the second parameter to the constructor: `PopupMenu(this, anchorView)`.
3. We set up the `OnClickListener` for the anchor view to show the `PopupMenu` when clicked.

By providing an anchor view, the `PopupMenu` will be positioned relative to that view, and the `MenuPopupHelper` will be able to display the menu correctly.

Make sure to replace `R.id.anchorView` with the actual ID of the view you want to use as the anchor for the `PopupMenu`. This view should be present in your layout file (`your_layout.xml`).

If you're using a `Fragment` instead of an `Activity`, you can follow a similar approach by finding the anchor view within the `Fragment` and passing it to the `PopupMenu` constructor.

