Based on the provided codebase context, you can hide the `Toolbar` per Fragment by overriding the `onCreateOptionsMenu` and `onPrepareOptionsMenu` methods in your Fragment class.

Here's an example of how you can implement this in the `DeliveryAddressFragment.kt` file:

```kotlin
override fun onCreateOptionsMenu(menu: Menu, inflater: MenuInflater) {
    // Inflate the menu resource
    inflater.inflate(R.menu.toolbar_menu, menu)
    super.onCreateOptionsMenu(menu, inflater)
}

override fun onPrepareOptionsMenu(menu: Menu) {
    // Hide or show the Toolbar menu items here
    val toolbar = (requireActivity() as AppCompatActivity).supportActionBar
    toolbar?.setDisplayHomeAsUpEnabled(false) // Hide the "Up" button
    toolbar?.setDisplayShowTitleEnabled(false) // Hide the title

    // You can also hide specific menu items if needed
    menu.findItem(R.id.home_button)?.isVisible = false // Hide the "Home" button

    super.onPrepareOptionsMenu(menu)
}
```

In the `onCreateOptionsMenu` method, you inflate the `toolbar_menu.xml` resource to populate the `Toolbar` with menu items.

In the `onPrepareOptionsMenu` method, you can access the `Toolbar` through the `supportActionBar` of the hosting `AppCompatActivity`. You can then use the `setDisplayHomeAsUpEnabled` and `setDisplayShowTitleEnabled` methods to hide or show the "Up" button and the title, respectively.

Additionally, you can use the `menu.findItem(R.id.home_button)?.isVisible = false` line to hide specific menu items, such as the "Home" button, by setting their visibility to `false`.

By overriding these methods in your Fragment class, you can control the visibility of the `Toolbar` and its menu items on a per-Fragment basis.

Note: Make sure to import the necessary classes and packages, such as `android.view.Menu`, `android.view.MenuInflater`, `androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity`, and `androidx.core.view.isVisible`.

