To hide the toolbar in the `LoginFragment`, you can modify the `MainActivity.kt` file and add a method to hide or show the toolbar based on the current Fragment or navigation destination.

Here's an example of how you can implement this:

1. In the `MainActivity.kt` file, add a method to hide or show the toolbar:

```kotlin
private fun showHideToolbar(shouldShow: Boolean) {
    supportActionBar?.let {
        if (shouldShow) {
            it.show()
        } else {
            it.hide()
        }
    }
}
```

2. In the `MainActivity.kt` file, override the `onDestinationChanged` method from the `NavController.OnDestinationChangedListener` interface to listen for navigation destination changes:

```kotlin
private val navControllerListener = NavController.OnDestinationChangedListener { _, destination, _ ->
    when (destination.id) {
        R.id.loginFragment -> showHideToolbar(false)
        else -> showHideToolbar(true)
    }
}
```

3. In the `onCreate` method of `MainActivity.kt`, set up the `navControllerListener`:

```kotlin
override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
    // ...
    navController.addOnDestinationChangedListener(navControllerListener)
}
```

4. In the `onDestroy` method of `MainActivity.kt`, remove the `navControllerListener`:

```kotlin
override fun onDestroy() {
    super.onDestroy()
    navController.removeOnDestinationChangedListener(navControllerListener)
}
```

With this implementation, whenever the navigation destination changes to the `loginFragment`, the `showHideToolbar(false)` method will be called, effectively hiding the toolbar. For all other destinations, the `showHideToolbar(true)` method will be called, showing the toolbar.

Note: Make sure to import the necessary classes and packages, such as `androidx.navigation.NavController` and `androidx.navigation.NavDestination`.

By following this approach, you can hide or show the toolbar based on the current navigation destination without modifying the `LoginFragment` itself.

