Based on the provided codebase context, you cannot call `InternetCheck.startMonitoring(requireContext())` globally because it requires a context object, which is typically available only within the scope of an Android component (e.g., Activity, Fragment, Service, etc.).

The `requireContext()` function is a part of the Fragment class and is used to retrieve the Context object associated with the Fragment instance. This Context object is required to access system services and resources.

However, you can call `InternetCheck.startMonitoring(requireContext())` from within the scope of a Fragment or an Activity. Here's an example of how you can call it in a Fragment:

```kotlin
class MyFragment : Fragment() {
    override fun onViewCreated(view: View, savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onViewCreated(view, savedInstanceState)

        InternetCheck.startMonitoring(requireContext()) { isConnected ->
            // Handle the internet connection status here
            // For example, you can update a UI element or perform other actions
            if (isConnected) {
                // Internet is available
            } else {
                // Internet is not available
            }
        }
    }

    override fun onDestroyView() {
        super.onDestroyView()
        InternetCheck.stopMonitoring()
    }
}
```

In this example, `InternetCheck.startMonitoring(requireContext())` is called within the `onViewCreated` lifecycle method of the Fragment. The `requireContext()` function provides the necessary Context object to the `startMonitoring` function.

If you need to start monitoring the internet connection globally, you can consider creating a singleton class or using a dependency injection framework like Dagger or Koin to provide the required Context object to the `InternetCheck` class.

Alternatively, you can create a separate class or a ViewModel that manages the internet connection monitoring and exposes the necessary methods or LiveData objects to other parts of your app. This way, you can start and stop the monitoring process from a central location and handle the connection status changes accordingly throughout your app.

