After reviewing the provided codebase context, specifically the `app\src\main\kotlin\com\elis\orderingapplication\LandingPageFragment.kt` file and the `app\src\main\res\layout-sw600dp\fragment_landing_page.xml` file, I can see the issue with the `debug_banner` still showing even though its visibility is set to `GONE`.

The issue seems to be in the `setFlavorBanner()` function in the `LandingPageFragment.kt` file. Here's the relevant code:

```kotlin
private fun setFlavorBanner() {
    // sets banner text
    if (sharedViewModel.flavor.value == "development") {
        binding.debugBanner.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.bannerText.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.debugBanner.setBackgroundColor(
            ContextCompat.getColor(
                requireContext(),
                R.color.purple_200
            )
        )
        binding.bannerText.text = resources.getString(R.string.devFlavorText)
    }
    // hides banner if PROD application
    if (sharedViewModel.flavor.value == "production") {
        binding.debugBanner.visibility = View.GONE
        binding.bannerText.visibility = View.GONE
    }
    // sets banner text and banner color
    if (sharedViewModel.flavor.value == "staging") {
        binding.debugBanner.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.bannerText.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.debugBanner.setBackgroundColor(
            ContextCompat.getColor(
                requireContext(),
                R.color.elis_orange
            )
        )
        binding.bannerText.text = resources.getString(R.string.testFlavorText)
    }
}
```

The issue is that the `setFlavorBanner()` function is setting the visibility of the `debug_banner` and `bannerText` based on the value of `sharedViewModel.flavor.value`. If the flavor is "development" or "staging", the visibility is set to `VISIBLE`, but if the flavor is "production", the visibility is set to `GONE`.

However, the problem is that if the flavor is "development" or "staging", the visibility is being set to `VISIBLE` again after the "production" check, overriding the `GONE` visibility.

To fix this issue, you can modify the `setFlavorBanner()` function to use an `else if` statement instead of separate `if` statements. Here's the modified code:

```kotlin
private fun setFlavorBanner() {
    if (sharedViewModel.flavor.value == "development") {
        binding.debugBanner.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.bannerText.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.debugBanner.setBackgroundColor(
            ContextCompat.getColor(
                requireContext(),
                R.color.purple_200
            )
        )
        binding.bannerText.text = resources.getString(R.string.devFlavorText)
    } else if (sharedViewModel.flavor.value == "production") {
        binding.debugBanner.visibility = View.GONE
        binding.bannerText.visibility = View.GONE
    } else if (sharedViewModel.flavor.value == "staging") {
        binding.debugBanner.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.bannerText.visibility = View.VISIBLE
        binding.debugBanner.setBackgroundColor(
            ContextCompat.getColor(
                requireContext(),
                R.color.elis_orange
            )
        )
        binding.bannerText.text = resources.getString(R.string.testFlavorText)
    }
}
```

With this modification, the `debug_banner` and `bannerText` visibility will be set correctly based on the flavor value. If the flavor is "production", the visibility will be set to `GONE`, and it won't be overridden by the subsequent `if` statements.

After making this change, the `debug_banner` should no longer show when the visibility is set to `GONE` in the `fragment_landing_page.xml` layout file for tablet devices (layout-sw600dp).

