In the `OrdersTabLayout.kt` file, you need to use a `FragmentStateAdapter` or a `FragmentPagerAdapter` to provide the fragments to be displayed in the `ViewPager2`. These adapters are specifically designed to manage fragments for a `ViewPager` or `ViewPager2`.

Here's an example of how you can create a `FragmentStateAdapter` for the `ViewPager2` in the `OrdersTabLayout.kt` file:

```kotlin
class OrdersTabLayout : Fragment() {
    // ...

    override fun onViewCreated(view: View, savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onViewCreated(view, savedInstanceState)

        // Initialize the TabLayout and ViewPager2
        tabLayout = binding.tabLayout
        viewPager = binding.viewPager

        // Set up the ViewPager adapter
        val adapter = ViewPagerAdapter(this)
        viewPager.adapter = adapter

        // Link the TabLayout and ViewPager
        TabLayoutMediator(tabLayout, viewPager) { tab, position ->
            tab.text = when (position) {
                0 -> "Tab 1"
                1 -> "Tab 2"
                else -> throw IllegalArgumentException("Invalid position")
            }
        }.attach()
    }

    // ...
}

class ViewPagerAdapter(fragment: Fragment) : FragmentStateAdapter(fragment) {

    override fun getItemCount(): Int = 2 // Number of tabs/fragments

    override fun createFragment(position: Int): Fragment {
        return when (position) {
            0 -> YourFirstFragment() // Replace with your actual fragment
            1 -> YourSecondFragment() // Replace with your actual fragment
            else -> throw IllegalArgumentException("Invalid position")
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `ViewPagerAdapter` class extends `FragmentStateAdapter` and provides the fragments to be displayed in each tab of the `ViewPager2`. The `createFragment` method returns the appropriate fragment instance based on the position.

You can replace `YourFirstFragment` and `YourSecondFragment` with your actual fragment classes that will be displayed in the respective tabs.

