        }
    }
}
```

The issue here is that the `startInternetCheckJob()` method is launching a coroutine within the `lifecycleScope` of the Fragment, and this coroutine runs indefinitely (`while (isActive)`) until the Fragment is destroyed.

Within this coroutine, the `sendOrderToSOL()` method is called when the internet is available, and the `sendOrderToSOL()` method itself launches another coroutine using `viewLifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope.launch`.

The problem arises when the Fragment's view is destroyed (e.g., when navigating away from the Fragment) while the coroutine launched in `startInternetCheckJob()` is still running. In this case, the `viewLifecycleOwner` becomes null, and when the `sendOrderToSOL()` method tries to access `viewLifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope.launch`, it throws the `java.lang.IllegalStateException: Can't access the Fragment View's LifecycleOwner for ArticleEntryCardFragment{...} when getView() is null i.e., before onCreateView() or after onDestroyView()` error.

To fix this issue, you should consider canceling or stopping the coroutine launched in `startInternetCheckJob()` when the Fragment's view is destroyed. You can do this by overriding the `onDestroyView()` method in the `ArticleEntryCardFragment` and canceling the coroutine there.

